No, Corey, I think that's quite important because when I was asked by the Aspect Board to take over the multi-strat program, we spent quite a few sessions actually just narrowing down what the objectives are because I think you've hit the nail on the head. The objectives should really fit into the design of the program. And I don't think it doesn't for a number of other cases that have come across, you sort of fall into, okay, this is an interesting program and now let's retroactively figure out what the utility function of this program is. But I've learned over the so many years of building systematic strategies that actually nailing down that what is a utility function, what niche is it trying to cater to, what's the client utility here, especially when you are working in a firm like Aspect that has a number of systematic strategies, it becomes quite important to establish what the utility function of each of our programs is because we don't want to muddy the water. We want to be quite clear to offer the investors the right product. So the objective here is, in my mind, quite simple. It's a multi-strategy, multi-product program. It's not a combination of all the models that we have at Aspect. We have currently over 250 individual forecasting models. So it's not a combination of everything that we do. And that's because we are trying to deliver our investors a smooth, consistent return profile with diversification to any of the risk factors and more importantly, to equity markets, to bond markets and to trend and macro. So any sort of common hedge fund indices and to any of the common systematic factors that you come across. It's a very simple objective. I think it's not as easy to achieve and it gets harder with every passing day. And so what do I mean by smoothness and consistency in return profile? With systematic strategies, the favorite question of clients and prospects is, which environment is the strategy supposed to work in and which environment is it not supposed to work in? But by definition, I'm trying to deliver you a consistent, smooth return profile. So it's supposed to work in all environments. Well, is it an all weather product? Well, I'm not very fond of that term all weather because it means, you know, it sort of discounts what we're trying to do here. You know, we're trying to combine a set of alpha models, forecasting models, return forecasters to deliver a consistent return stream that is going to deliver you returns in every environment that the world may throw upon us.
